[{"id":"5946cafc","elType":"container","settings":{"eael_image_masking_custom_clip_path":"clip-path: polygon(50% 0%, 80% 10%, 100% 35%, 100% 70%, 80% 90%, 50% 100%, 20% 90%, 0% 70%, 0% 35%, 20% 10%);","eael_image_masking_custom_clip_path_hover":"clip-path: polygon(50% 0%, 80% 10%, 100% 35%, 100% 70%, 80% 90%, 50% 100%, 20% 90%, 0% 70%, 0% 35%, 20% 10%);"},"elements":[{"id":"a30d92a","elType":"widget","settings":{"editor":"<p><em>By Nalla’s Dad / April 16, 2026</em></p><p><em>Affiliate disclosure: Some links below are Amazon affiliate links. Purchases support this site at no extra cost to you. Full disclosure: I only list products I’d genuinely consider for Nalla — and she’s pickier than a food critic with a Yelp grudge.</em></p><figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img class="wp-image-3588" src="https://dogfoodandfun.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/raw-dog-food-guide-2026-hero.jpg" alt="Happy dog with raw food bowl - best raw dog food guide 2026" /></figure><h2>The Morning Nalla Became a Food Snob</h2><p>It happened on a Tuesday. I poured Nalla’s usual kibble into her bowl — the same premium brand she’d eaten happily for two years — and she walked up, gave it one sniff, looked me dead in the eyes with an expression that clearly said “you can’t be serious,” and walked away.</p><p>No drama. No barking. Just the quiet, devastating disappointment of a dog who’d discovered she’d been eating the canine equivalent of microwave dinners her whole life.</p><p>See, the day before, a friend had brought over some raw turkey patties from We Feed Raw as a sample. Nalla inhaled them in about 45 seconds flat — a personal record, and she once ate half a shawarma off the sidewalk in Tel Aviv in under 10 seconds. One taste of the good stuff and apparently two years of premium kibble loyalty meant absolutely nothing. Dogs are ruthless.</p><p>As a software engineer, I approach most problems the same way: panic briefly, then open a spreadsheet. So when Nalla staged her one-dog kibble rebellion, I did what any reasonable person would do — I tracked her weight, coat condition, energy levels, stool quality (glamorous, I know), and monthly food cost for 8 straight weeks. My wife thought I’d lost it. Nalla thought she’d won. Spoiler: they were both right.</p><h2>What Is Raw Dog Food? (Besides Expensive)</h2><p>Raw dog food isn’t one thing — it’s a whole spectrum, ranging from “I bought a bag at PetSmart” to “I’m in my kitchen at 6 AM deboning a duck while questioning my life choices.” Let me break down the options.</p><h3>BARF (Yes, That’s Really the Name)</h3><p>BARF stands for Biologically Appropriate Raw Food, developed by veterinarian Dr. Ian Billinghurst — who clearly did not run the name by marketing first. It follows a ratio of 60-80% raw meaty bones, 20-25% vegetables and fruits, and 5-10% organ meats. When Nalla eats BARF-style meals, I aim for roughly 70% muscle meat and bone, 10% organ, 10% vegetables, and 10% fruit or supplements. She aims for 100% meat and 0% vegetables, but we compromise.</p><h3>PMR (Prey Model Raw)</h3><p>PMR skips the vegetables entirely and aims to replicate what a wild canine would eat: 80% muscle meat, 10% raw edible bone, 5% liver, and 5% other organs. It’s the “dogs are wolves, Karen” approach. Simpler to prepare but requires more attention to nutritional completeness. Brands like Viva Raw follow this model closely. Nalla would vote for this one if she could.</p><h3>Commercial Raw (The “I Have a Job” Option)</h3><p>Pre-made patties, nuggets, or freeze-dried meals that are nutritionally balanced right out of the bag. This is the “I want raw but I also need to be at my desk by 9 AM and I’m not butchering a rabbit before coffee” option. The cost is higher ($3-9/day depending on brand and dog size) but the convenience and safety margins are worth it while you figure out what you’re doing. This is where I started with Nalla, and honestly where 90% of people should start unless you really enjoy handling raw chicken before sunrise.</p><h2>What Actually Happened: The 8-Week Spreadsheet of Truth</h2><p>I went into this as a skeptic. I’d read the marketing claims — shinier coat! more energy! smaller stools! — and figured most of it was placebo effect from owners who’d just spent $200 on fancy dog food and needed to justify the credit card bill. But my spreadsheet doesn’t care about feelings.</p><h3>Coat and Skin: The “What Shampoo Do You Use?” Phase</h3><p>By week 3, Nalla’s coat had a noticeable sheen that her kibble never produced. And before you say confirmation bias — my wife, who thought the whole raw experiment was “the dumbest thing you’ve done since buying that standing desk treadmill,” was the one who pointed it out first. She actually asked if I’d switched Nalla’s shampoo. I hadn’t. I’d switched her food from processed brown pellets to actual turkey. Revolutionary stuff.</p><p>The science is straightforward: raw food typically contains 15-25% fat versus 8-12% in most kibble. A Cornell nutrition professor confirmed that the shinier coat is really just a high-fat diet effect — achievable with any high-fat food. But hey, it works, and Nalla looks like she just walked out of a doggy salon.</p><h3>Digestion: The Metrics Nobody Wants to Discuss at Dinner</h3><p>This is the unsexy metric that actually matters, and I’m going to talk about it because nobody else will. On kibble, Nalla’s stools were large, soft, and operated on their own unpredictable schedule. By week 4 of raw, they were smaller, firmer, and consistent enough to set a watch by. Volume decreased by roughly 40%.</p><p>Less waste out = more nutrition absorbed. Engineer math at its finest. My wife was less impressed by the math and more impressed by the significantly smaller bags on our walks. Wins are wins.</p><h3>Energy: From Post-Meal Coma to “Let’s Go Already”</h3><p>On kibble, Nalla would eat and then faceplant on the couch for 90 minutes like she’d just finished Thanksgiving dinner. On raw, she’d eat and be nudging me toward the door within 20 minutes. Whether that’s better digestion or just a lighter stomach, I can’t say scientifically. But it was consistent — and slightly inconvenient when I was trying to finish a deployment.</p><h3>Dental Health: The Breath Situation</h3><p>After 8 weeks, noticeably less plaque buildup. Raw meaty bones provide natural mechanical scraping that kibble can’t replicate. And Nalla’s breath improved from “biohazard” to merely “dog.” My wife says this alone justified the entire experiment. I’m choosing not to be offended by her priorities.</p><h2>The Real Risks: Because I’m Not Going to Lie to You</h2><p>Here’s where I take off the raw-feeding cheerleader hat and put on the engineer hat. Raw feeding has real risks. Pretending otherwise would make me no better than the kibble companies who slap “premium” on bags of corn filler.</p><h3>Bacteria: The 1-in-3 Problem</h3><p>An FDA study found that roughly 1 in 3 frozen raw pet food products contain Salmonella, Listeria, or toxigenic E. coli. That’s not a rounding error — that’s a coin flip plus some. The CDC, FDA, and Canadian Veterinary Medical Association all officially recommend against raw feeding, and they’re not saying it for fun.</p><p>In our kitchen, we treat Nalla’s raw food exactly like we treat raw chicken for ourselves: dedicated cutting board, immediate cleanup, hand washing that would satisfy a surgeon, and all her bowls go through the dishwasher after every meal. Six months in, zero issues. But the precautions are non-negotiable — this isn’t the place to be lazy.</p><h3>Nutritional Roulette</h3><p>Multiple studies found that homemade raw diets frequently have dangerous nutritional deficiencies or excesses — particularly calcium, phosphorus, and vitamin D. This is the #1 reason I recommend starting with commercial raw: brands like We Feed Raw and Open Farm are formulated to meet AAFCO standards, so you’re not accidentally giving your dog the nutritional equivalent of eating nothing but steak for a year.</p><h3>Bones: Proceed with Common Sense</h3><p>Raw bones can chip teeth and pose choking hazards. Nalla handles chicken necks and duck frames like a champ, but I never give her weight-bearing bones from large animals (like beef marrow bones) — they’re basically nature’s jawbreakers. If your dog is a gulper who treats food like a speed-eating competition, skip recreational bones entirely and use ground bone in the food instead.</p><h3>The Antibiotic Resistance Thing Nobody Talks About</h3><p>Raw pet food frequently exceeds hygiene thresholds for bacteria that carry resistance to important antibiotics. This is a genuine public health concern — especially if you have young kids, elderly family members, or immunocompromised individuals sharing the house. It’s not a reason to skip raw necessarily, but it IS a reason to take food handling seriously and not let your dog lick the counter after eating.</p><h2>The 10-Day Transition Plan (That Nalla Completed in 7 Because She’s Impatient)</h2><p>Don’t go cold turkey. Well, unless your dog goes cold turkey for you, like Nalla did. For the rest of you with less dramatic dogs, here’s the protocol:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Days</th><th>Kibble</th><th>Raw</th><th>What to Expect</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1-3</td><td>75%</td><td>25%</td><td>Start with chicken or turkey. Your dog will look at you like “finally.”</td></tr><tr><td>4-6</td><td>50%</td><td>50%</td><td>Some soft stools — normal. Don’t panic. Don’t Google it at 2 AM.</td></tr><tr><td>7-9</td><td>25%</td><td>75%</td><td>If stools are solid, you’re winning at life.</td></tr><tr><td>10+</td><td>0%</td><td>100%</td><td>Full raw. Introduce a second protein after 2 weeks. Celebrate quietly.</td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong>Transition survival tips:</strong></p><ul><li>Start with boneless chicken or turkey — lowest fat, easiest to digest, least likely to cause a 3 AM emergency</li><li>Feed raw and kibble in <strong>separate meals</strong> (morning kibble, evening raw) rather than mixing in the same bowl — the digestion rates are different</li><li>Keep portions at your dog’s current calorie level — overfeeding because you’re excited is a real thing and I definitely didn’t do it (I did)</li><li>If diarrhea lasts more than 48 hours, slow down and go back one step. No shame in reverse</li><li>Add <a href="https://dogfoodandfun.com/canned-pumpkin-dogs-guide/">canned pumpkin for digestive support</a> — 1 tablespoon per meal works wonders. Nalla thinks it’s a treat. Don’t tell her.</li></ul><p>Nalla’s transition was 7 days instead of 10 because she essentially fired her kibble on day 1. Her stools were slightly soft on days 3-5 but normalized by day 7. Your dog may take 2-3 weeks. Every gut is different. Mine certainly is after eating Nalla’s leftover turkey at midnight once. Don’t ask.</p><h2>Best Commercial Raw Dog Foods 2026: Honest Reviews From Someone Who’s Cleaned Up the Aftermath</h2><p>I’ve tried five brands with Nalla over the past 6 months. No sponsorships, no affiliate pressure, no brand sent me free product in exchange for a glowing review. Just a software engineer, his opinionated dog, and a spreadsheet.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Brand</th><th>Type</th><th>Cost/Day (35lb dog)</th><th>Proteins</th><th>The Good</th><th>The Not-So-Good</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>We Feed Raw Turkey</strong></td><td>Frozen</td><td>$5-7</td><td>8</td><td>USDA meats, easy portioning, Nalla’s #1 pick</td><td>Your freezer will look like a crime scene</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Maev Raw Beef</strong></td><td>Frozen</td><td>$6-9</td><td>4</td><td>5-star DFA rating, 47% protein, added superfoods</td><td>Priced like it contains actual gold flakes</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Open Farm Freeze-Dried</strong></td><td>Freeze-dried</td><td>$4-6</td><td>3</td><td>Grass-fed beef, no freezer needed, great for travel</td><td>Looks like astronaut food. Needs rehydration.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Stella &amp; Chewy Rabbit</strong></td><td>Freeze-dried</td><td>$3-5</td><td>12+</td><td>Widest protein variety, available everywhere</td><td>Smaller patties — Nalla finishes them suspiciously fast</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Instinct Raw Chicken</strong></td><td>Frozen</td><td>$2-4</td><td>6</td><td>Most affordable, cage-free, good for puppies</td><td>Higher carb content. The Honda Civic of raw food.</td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong>Our pick:</strong> We Feed Raw for home (Nalla would riot if I switched) with Stella &amp; Chewy freeze-dried as the travel backup. Total monthly damage for a 35-lb dog: approximately $150-180/month, compared to $65-80/month on premium kibble. Yes, it’s basically doubled our dog food budget. No, my wife has not fully forgiven me. But Nalla’s coat is fantastic, so I consider it a win.</p><h2>DIY Raw: Nalla’s Sunday Meal Prep (AKA My Glamorous Weekend)</h2><p>Once I got comfortable with commercial raw, I started supplementing with homemade meals 2-3 days per week to save money. Every Sunday morning, while normal people drink coffee and relax, I’m in the kitchen portioning raw turkey into silicone molds like a very specific type of weirdo.</p><h3>Weekly Shopping List (3 days of meals)</h3><ul><li>2 lbs boneless turkey thighs — ~$6</li><li>0.5 lbs chicken liver — ~$2 (the butcher definitely judges me)</li><li>0.5 lbs chicken hearts — ~$3</li><li>1 cup mixed vegetables (broccoli, carrots, spinach) — ~$2</li><li>2 eggs with shell for calcium — ~$1</li><li>1 tbsp fish oil — ~$0.50</li></ul><p><strong>Total: ~$14.50 for 3 days = ~$4.83/day</strong></p><p>That’s about 15-30% cheaper than commercial raw. The trade-off is 45 minutes of Sunday prep and the constant smell of raw turkey in your kitchen. Nalla supervises the entire process from her spot 6 inches from my feet, drooling like a fountain.</p><p><strong>Important reality check:</strong> This recipe alone is NOT nutritionally complete. I use a Balance IT supplement to cover micronutrients, and I rotate proteins weekly. If you’re going full DIY, invest in a consultation with a board-certified veterinary nutritionist ($200-400 one-time). It’s absolutely worth not accidentally malnourishing your dog because you read a recipe on Reddit. For more tested recipes, check our <a href="https://dogfoodandfun.com/recipes/">homemade dog food recipes</a> — all Nalla-tested, all safe ingredients.</p><h2>When Raw Isn’t the Move</h2><p>Raw isn’t right for every dog, and pretending otherwise would be irresponsible. Based on research and real conversations in <a href="https://dogfoodandfun.com/grain-free-dcm-taurine-truth/">dog nutrition groups where people have Very Strong Opinions</a>:</p><ul><li><strong>Immunocompromised dogs</strong> — dogs on chemo or immunosuppressive drugs can’t fight foodborne pathogens as well. Stick with cooked or commercial.</li><li><strong>Puppies under 12 weeks</strong> — their immune systems are still figuring things out. Use puppy-formulated commercial raw (like Instinct Puppy) if you must, but honestly, quality kibble is fine here.</li><li><strong>Dogs with pancreatitis history</strong> — raw tends to be higher in fat. You’ll need a specifically low-fat formulation, and probably a vet who won’t lecture you.</li><li><strong>Households with babies or immunocompromised humans</strong> — the bacterial risk isn’t just about your dog. If grandma’s visiting for three months, maybe pause the raw experiment.</li></ul><p>Nalla is a healthy, active 3-year-old with zero chronic conditions and the immune system of a dog who’s eaten questionable things off Tel Aviv sidewalks and survived. She’s basically the ideal raw candidate.</p><h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2><p><script type="application/ld+json">
