</script></p><h3>Is raw dog food actually better than kibble?</h3><p>Depends on the dog, the diet, and how much you enjoy spending money. In our experience with Nalla, raw produced measurable improvements in coat, digestion, and dental health over 8 weeks. But a poorly balanced raw diet can actually be worse than quality kibble. Start with AAFCO-compliant commercial brands — they’ve done the nutritional math so you don’t have to.</p><h3>How much does raw dog food cost per month?</h3><p>For a 35-pound dog like Nalla: $90-270/month for commercial raw (depending on whether you go budget Instinct or bougie Maev), ~$120-150/month for DIY with supplements, versus $65-80/month for premium kibble. Yes, your dog’s food budget may now exceed your own. Welcome to raw feeding.</p><h3>How do I transition from kibble to raw?</h3><p>Slowly. 10 days: start at 75/25 kibble/raw, work your way to full raw. Start with chicken or turkey. Feed them in separate meals. If things get… messy… for more than 48 hours, slow down. Pumpkin is your friend. Patience is your other friend.</p><h3>Can I make raw dog food at home?</h3><p>Yes, but please don’t just wing it. Studies show most homemade raw diets have serious nutritional gaps. Get a Balance IT supplement at minimum, or spring for a veterinary nutritionist consultation ($200-400). Your dog’s skeleton will thank you.</p><h3>What are the risks?</h3><p>Bacteria (1-in-3 frozen raw products contain pathogens per FDA), nutritional imbalances if you DIY without guidance, bone choking hazards, and antibiotic resistance concerns. All manageable with proper handling and smart product choices — but not something to ignore because you watched a convincing Instagram reel.</p><h2>Related Reading</h2><ul><li>Confused about <a href="https://dogfoodandfun.com/grain-free-dcm-taurine-truth/">grain-free dog food and DCM</a>? Our deep dive separates the science from the social media panic.</li><li>Dog’s stomach need backup during the transition? Our <a href="https://dogfoodandfun.com/canned-pumpkin-dogs-guide/">canned pumpkin guide</a> has the exact dosing we use for Nalla (spoiler: she thinks it’s dessert).</li><li>Browse our full collection of <a href="https://dogfoodandfun.com/recipes/">homemade dog food recipes</a> — all tested on Nalla, all safe, all met with tail wags.</li><li>Our <a href="https://dogfoodandfun.com/dog-safe-grilled-salmon-with-vegetables-recipe/">grilled salmon recipe</a> is packed with omega-3s and makes a great raw-adjacent meal for dogs who are still on the fence.</li></ul><h2>The Bottom Line: Worth It, But Not Magic</h2><p>After 6 months of data, spreadsheets, raw turkey under my fingernails, and one very smug dog, here’s my honest engineer’s verdict: raw feeding improved Nalla’s coat, digestion, dental health, and post-meal energy. The benefits were measurable, not imagined. My spreadsheet confirms it. My wife reluctantly confirms it. Nalla aggressively confirms it every time she hears the freezer open.</p><p>But raw is not a magic bullet. It’s more expensive ($150-180/month versus $70 for kibble), requires more prep time, demands careful food safety practices, and carries real bacterial risks that kibble doesn’t. It’s not for every dog, every budget, or every lifestyle.</p><p>If you’re considering it: start with commercial raw like We Feed Raw or Stella &amp; Chewy. Transition slowly over 10 days. Track your dog’s response — actual data, not vibes. And if you go DIY, for the love of everything, get a nutritionist involved before you freestyle it.</p><p>Nalla hasn’t touched kibble since that fateful Tuesday. And honestly? Watching her sprint to her bowl every morning with the enthusiasm of a dog who genuinely loves mealtime — instead of the polite resignation of one who’s tolerating it — that’s worth the extra $100 a month.</p><p>Even if my wife disagrees.</p>","eael_vto_writing_gradient_color_repeater":[{"eael_vto_writing_gradient_color":"#7C62FF","eael_vto_writing_gradient_color_location":{"unit":"%","size":50},"_id":"8215893"},{"eael_vto_writing_gradient_color":"#FF6464","eael_vto_writing_gradient_color_location":{"unit":"%","size":90},"_id":"fdb7534"}],"eael_image_masking_custom_clip_path":"clip-path: polygon(50% 0%, 80% 10%, 100% 35%, 100% 70%, 80% 90%, 50% 100%, 20% 90%, 0% 70%, 0% 35%, 20% 10%);","eael_image_masking_custom_clip_path_hover":"clip-path: polygon(50% 0%, 80% 10%, 100% 35%, 100% 70%, 80% 90%, 50% 100%, 20% 90%, 0% 70%, 0% 35%, 20% 10%);"},"elements":[],"widgetType":"text-editor"}],"isInner":false}]
